# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# .env.test  —  Safe, fake values used when running automated tests
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Why a separate test file?
#   • Tests should NEVER hit real Google / Twilio / Groq APIs.
#     That would cost money, require a network connection, and make tests slow.
#   • Using fake values means tests run instantly, offline, and for free.
#   • The values below are obviously fake (no real credentials would look like this).
#
# How tests load this file:
#   In your test runner (e.g. pytest) you can do:
#     from dotenv import load_dotenv
#     load_dotenv(".env.test", override=True)
#   or set the environment variable:
#     ENV_FILE=.env.test pytest
# ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════


# ── Google OAuth (fake) ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These won't authenticate with Google — that's the point.
# Tests that exercise the OAuth flow should mock/stub the HTTP call instead.
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=test-client-id.apps.googleusercontent.com
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=test-client-secret
GOOGLE_REDIRECT_URI=http://localhost:3000/auth/callback


# ── Server ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Use a different port so tests don't clash with a running dev server
PORT=3001


# ── AI Chat (Groq) — fake ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The chat route should be tested with a mocked HTTP response, not a real call.
GROQ_API_KEY=test-groq-key-not-real


# ── SMS (Twilio) — fake ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Using Twilio's test credentials format — these are recognised as test values
# and will never actually send an SMS or charge your account.
TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID=ACtest00000000000000000000000000000
TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN=test_auth_token_not_real
TWILIO_FROM=+15005550006
TWILIO_TO=+15005550006
